han echoing Schelling's Philosophy of Art?Mourning Philology draws on Varuzhan and his work to present a history of the national imagination, which is also a history of national philology, as a reaction to the two main philological inventions of the nineteenth century: mythological religion and the native. In its first part, the book thus gives an account of the successive stages of orientalist philology. The last episode in this story of national emergence took place in 1914 in Constantinople, when the literary journal Mehyan gathered around Varuzhan the great names to come of Armenian literature in the diaspora  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aArmenian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aArt and literaturezArmenia. 0aReligion and literaturexGoshgarian. 0aReligion and literaturezArmenia. 4aArmenian literature. 4aMythological religion. 4aNationalism. 4aOrientalism. 4aOttoman empire. 4aPhilology. 4aPhilosophy of art. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aFort, Jeff1 aGoshgarian, G. M.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823255269zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823255269423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823255269.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK